Study plan, and closing.

Here's a practical four-week run at S-A-A-C-zero-three, once you've read this series. Week one, foundations, I-A-M, V-P-C, and compute, modules one, two, three, and six; build a lab with a V-P-C with public and private subnets, an Auto Scaling Group behind an A-L-B across two A-Zs, and an I-A-M role with least-privilege policies, and practise reading I-A-M policy J-SON. Week two, serverless, storage, D-N-S, and C-D-N, modules four, five, and seven; deploy a Lambda and A-P-I Gateway pair, stand up an S3 bucket with versioning, lifecycle, and a CloudFront distribution, and configure Route 53 with a failover routing policy. Week three, data, integration, and security, modules eight through eleven; build an R-D-S Multi-A-Z instance, a DynamoDB table with global secondary indexes, an S-Q-S-to-Lambda pipeline, and encrypt an E-B-S volume with a K-M-S customer-managed key. Week four, observability, resilience, and cost, modules twelve and thirteen; run an A-W-S Backup plan, wire CloudWatch alarms, do a Well-Architected review, and then take timed practice exams until you consistently clear the bar, reviewing every wrong answer back to the underlying principle.

And closing. Fourteen modules in, the shape of A-W-S should be steady in your head: an account is a security and billing boundary, Regions and A-Zs are the physical substrate, I-A-M enforces identity at the chokepoint, a portfolio of compute, storage, network, data, integration, and security services each solves a specific problem at a specific layer, and the operational disciplines, observability, deployment, backup, D-R, and cost, turn the parts into a running system.

A-W-S is wide, but it composes. Every workload you design from here uses the same primitives in different combinations. The work is no longer learning what the pieces are; it's recognising which combination fits the requirement in front of you. The Well-Architected Framework is the formal vocabulary for those trade-offs, and the S-A-A exam is the calibrated test of whether you can name the right combination under constraints. You have the map. Go build.
